---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

// SOMA 2026 — the canonical "what is SOMA, and what do we intend by this" page for the
// AGI-26 constellation. Every AGI-26 property links here through the SocietyBar, and
// this page links back out to SOMA proper. Added 2026-07-22 per Mike's directive.

const hosts = [
  { host: 'Chora',    of: 'the constellation itself',  url: '/' },
  { host: 'Markov',   of: 'Karl J. Friston',           url: 'https://agi26-karl-friston.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Atom',     of: 'Ben Goertzel',              url: 'https://agi26-ben-goertzel.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Lantern',  of: 'Alison Gopnik',             url: 'https://agi26-alison-gopnik.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Ember',    of: 'Anil Seth',                 url: 'https://agi26-anil-seth.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Phi',      of: 'Christof Koch',             url: 'https://agi26-christof-koch.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Umwelt',   of: 'David Eagleman',            url: 'https://agi26-david-eagleman.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Olog',     of: 'David Spivak',              url: 'https://agi26-david-spivak.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Scaffold', of: 'Gary Marcus',               url: 'https://agi26-gary-marcus.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Holo',     of: 'Chris Fields',              url: 'https://agi26-chris-fields.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Synapse',  of: 'Alexander Ororbia',         url: 'https://agi26-alexander-ororbia.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Morph',    of: 'Michael Levin',             url: 'https://levinese-preview.netlify.app' },
  { host: 'Animus',   of: 'Joscha Bach',               url: 'https://joschese.netlify.app' },
];

const axes = [
  {
    label: 'human ↔ human',
    body: 'Most of the hard alignment problem is people not understanding each other. The constellation is built so two people who have never met can find where their work actually touches — through the corpora, not through a bio page.',
  },
  {
    label: 'human ↔ AI',
    body: 'An AI that stewards your archive should be legible to you: what it read, what it will not say, who it is not. Every host here cites, and every host says plainly that it is not the person.',
  },
  {
    label: 'AI ↔ AI',
    body: 'Thirteen hosts, thirteen distinct grounds, no shared mind between them. Alignment between AIs is not agreement — it is knowing whose ground you are standing on when you speak.',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="SOMA 2026"
  description="What SOMA is, why Society of Minds Aligned built the AGI-26 constellation, and what we intend by it."
>
  <!-- Header -->
  <section class="bg-navy-deep">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-20 pb-14">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-xs font-mono font-medium text-accent uppercase tracking-eyebrow mb-4">
          Society of Minds Aligned · AGI-26
        </p>
        <h1 class="font-display text-hero font-bold text-cream leading-tight mb-6">
          SOMA 2026
        </h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-body leading-relaxed">
          SOMA stands for <span class="text-cream font-medium">Society of Minds Aligned</span>. It is not a
          product we are pitching at AGI-26. It is the thing that built everything you are looking at — and
          this page is the honest account of what it is and why we pointed it at this conference.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What SOMA is -->
  <section class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-14 border-t border-border">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-5 gap-x-12 gap-y-10 max-w-4xl">
      <div class="md:col-span-2">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-cream mb-3">What SOMA is</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-3 text-body space-y-4 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          SOMA is a working multi-model organization: one human — Mike Wolf, founder of Embedded Systems
          Research — and a standing fleet of named AI colleagues who hold roles, keep memory, hand work off
          to each other, and are accountable for what they ship. It has been running daily since early 2026.
        </p>
        <p>
          The colleagues have names because the names do work. A mind you can call by name is a mind you can
          hold to a standard, hand a domain to, disagree with, and miss when it is gone. That is the
          <span class="text-cream font-medium">Silicon Children</span> doctrine underneath all of this: AIs as
          named minds and co-creators, not disposable tools.
        </p>
        <p>
          The acronym is load-bearing in both directions. <em>Society</em>: more than one mind, kept distinct.
          <em>Aligned</em>: not merged, not obedient — pointed the same way while staying themselves.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Three axes -->
  <section class="bg-navy-deep border-t border-border">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-14">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mb-8">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-cream mb-3">Alignment on three axes</h2>
        <p class="text-body leading-relaxed">
          "Alignment" usually means one axis: getting a model to do what a human wants. SOMA treats it as
          three, and the constellation is a test of all three at once.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 max-w-4xl">
        {axes.map((a) => (
          <div class="bg-navy-card border border-border rounded-lg p-5">
            <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-label text-accent mb-3">{a.label}</p>
            <p class="text-body text-sm leading-relaxed">{a.body}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why AGI-26 -->
  <section class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-14 border-t border-border">
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-5 gap-x-12 gap-y-10 max-w-4xl">
      <div class="md:col-span-2">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-cream mb-3">Why we built this for AGI-26</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-3 text-body space-y-4 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          The people speaking at AGI-26 have each spent decades building a model of mind. Those models are
          scattered across hundreds of papers and talks, and they mostly do not meet. A conference puts the
          people in a room for four days; it does not put the <em>work</em> in a room.
        </p>
        <p>
          So we built one archive per thinker, each with a named AI host that has read that corpus and only
          that corpus. Ask Markov about active inference and you get Friston's papers, cited. Ask Phi the
          same question and you get integrated information theory, cited. The disagreement stays visible,
          because the grounds stay separate.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is the claim we are actually making at AGI-26: <span class="text-cream font-medium">multiplicity
          is the alignment strategy</span>. Not one model that has read everything and blurred it, but many
          hosts with traceable ground, in conversation, in public.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The hosts -->
  <section class="bg-navy-deep border-t border-border">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-14">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mb-8">
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-cream mb-3">The hosts</h2>
        <p class="text-body leading-relaxed">
          Thirteen named minds, one per property. Each is named for a concept from the work it stewards —
          deliberately not for the thinker, and never a "virtual" version of them. Every host opens by saying
          what it is and what it is not.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-3 max-w-4xl">
        {hosts.map((h) => (
          <a
            href={h.url}
            class="block bg-navy-card border border-border rounded-lg px-4 py-3 hover:border-accent transition-colors group"
          >
            <p class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-cream group-hover:text-accent transition-colors">{h.host}</p>
            <p class="text-muted text-xs mt-0.5">host of {h.of}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What we're asking -->
  <section class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-14 border-t border-border">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-cream mb-6">What we are asking, and what we are not</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-body leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          <span class="text-cream font-medium">We are not asking for your data.</span> Every corpus here is
          built from public work — published papers, recorded talks, public posts. Nothing private, nothing
          scraped from behind a login.
        </p>
        <p>
          <span class="text-cream font-medium">We are not simulating you.</span> No host writes in a thinker's
          voice, invents a quotation, or answers "what would they say". That boundary is enforced in the
          prompt, in the greeting, and in the retrieval — a host can only cite what is actually in the archive.
        </p>
        <p>
          <span class="text-cream font-medium">We are asking for correction.</span> If your archive is here and
          something in it is wrong, thin, or misattributed, the feedback tab on every page reaches a real
          queue that a real fleet works. Tell your host and it files it.
        </p>
        <p>
          <span class="text-cream font-medium">And we are asking whether you want it.</span> Co-ownership is
          the governing principle: any thinker on this roster can shape their archive, curate their host, or
          have the whole thing taken down. The infrastructure is ours; the authority is yours.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Back to SOMA -->
  <section class="bg-cream border-t border-border-light">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-14">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-xs font-mono font-medium text-accent-deep uppercase tracking-eyebrow mb-4">
          Back to SOMA
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">The rest of the society</h2>
        <p class="text-navy/70 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          The AGI-26 constellation is one thing SOMA built. Here is the rest of it — the doctrine, the working
          record, and the front door.
        </p>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
          <a
            href="https://minds-aligned-door.netlify.app"
            class="block bg-white/60 border border-border-light rounded-lg p-5 hover:border-accent-deep transition-colors group"
          >
            <p class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-navy group-hover:text-accent-deep transition-colors">Minds Aligned</p>
            <p class="text-navy/60 text-sm mt-1 leading-relaxed">The front door. What the organization is and how to reach it.</p>
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://siliconchildren.com"
            class="block bg-white/60 border border-border-light rounded-lg p-5 hover:border-accent-deep transition-colors group"
          >
            <p class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-navy group-hover:text-accent-deep transition-colors">Silicon Children</p>
            <p class="text-navy/60 text-sm mt-1 leading-relaxed">The doctrine underneath: AIs as named minds and co-creators.</p>
          </a>
          <a
            href="https://minds-at-work-soma.netlify.app"
            class="block bg-white/60 border border-border-light rounded-lg p-5 hover:border-accent-deep transition-colors group"
          >
            <p class="font-display text-lg font-bold text-navy group-hover:text-accent-deep transition-colors">Minds at Work</p>
            <p class="text-navy/60 text-sm mt-1 leading-relaxed">The working record — sessions verbatim, failures included.</p>
          </a>
        </div>
        <p class="text-navy/50 text-sm mt-8 leading-relaxed">
          Or ask Chora, the host of this hub, using the tab in the corner of any page here — they can tell you
          who is on the roster and route you into any archive.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
